        h2 On geotagging

        p This project relies on tweets that are geotagged, either with exact coordinates or with a &ldquo;place&rdquo;. Coordinates, the most granular location type (as specific as a street intersection), are given by the phone&rsquo;s GPS as the place where someone is when they send the tweet. Place, a coarser location type, is a named location (business, city, country) around someone that they can choose before sending the tweet.

        p Geotagging is an incredible feature for researchers and data visualisers (not to mention, of course, business and advertisers). The &ldquo;big data&rdquo; method of data collection utilised prevalently on so many platforms&mdash;&ldquo;collect anything and everything that might be remotely insightful&rdquo;&mdash;allows a researcher to see detailed geospatial trends that are happening *right this moment* with just a few lines of code, whereas a pre-internet researcher may have had to ride on a bicycle around a region for years to be able to amass a large-ish amount of data.

        p However, while just over 3.5% of tweets were geotagged in 2012 (three years after geotagging was introduced on Twitter), that percentage has dropped steadily to around 1.5% of tweets since 2017 (#[a(href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/kalevleetaru/2019/03/04/visualizing-seven-years-of-twitters-evolution-2012-2018/#404c0cb07ccf") Kalev Leetaru, Forbes]&mdash;fascinating charts, by the way, if you&rsquo;re interested!). Our decreasing trust and interest in geotagging hints at the deep concerns we have about privacy today. There&rsquo;s a lack of transparency (we don&rsquo;t know when our location is being collected, how often, and how detailed) and a lack of agency (invisible defaults and slippery opt-outs instead of meaningful opt-ins can overwhelm and blindside). 

