        p Is this project an ethical use of the data I&rsquo;m able to access through Twitter? Without knowing whether all of the people are aware of and consenting to being geotagged (and rather suspecting many aren&rsquo;t), it&rsquo;s hard to say yes, but hopefully only showing truncated tweets without any personally revealing information provides enough anonymity for this to pass for the moment.

        h2 Some limitations

        p Owing to the limitations of both the standard plan and Twitter&rsquo;s own data parsing, there are a couple major factors that make the project less comprehensive and accurate than hoped.

        ul: li Languages

        blockquote(class="article-blockquote") Non-space separated languages, such as CJK are currently unsupported. &mdash;#[a(href="https://developer.twitter.com/en/docs/tweets/filter-realtime/guides/basic-stream-parameters") Standard stream parameters]

        p This project uses Twitter&rsquo;s Streaming API, with the &ldquo;statuses/filter&rdquo; endpoint. This means that a connection is constantly open between the app and Twitter, through which Twitter sends tweets in realtime that match with the keywords I specify in the &ldquo;track&rdquo; parameter. The explanation hints at spaces being a challenging technical hurdle&mdash;Twitter&rsquo;s algorithm for breaking a tweet down into keywords doesn&rsquo;t know what to do with a tweet written in languages like Chinese, Japanese, or Korean, which may lack word-separating spaces. Unfortunately, by multiple metrics, this leaves out a large population of people and internet users. On total number of speakers: combined varieties of Chinese bring it to 1st on the list, Japanese is 13th, and Korean is 22nd (#[a(href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_languages_by_total_number_of_speakers#Ethnologue_(2019,_23rd_edition)") 2019 Ethnologue]). On languages on the internet: Chinese is 2nd and Japanese is 8th (#[a(href="https://www.statista.com/statistics/262946/share-of-the-most-common-languages-on-the-internet/") Statista]). On languages on Twitter: Japanese is 2nd, Thai (another non-space separated language) is 9th, and Korean is 10th (#[a(href="https://mashable.com/2013/12/17/twitter-popular-languages/") Statista via Mashable]).

        figure(class="article-figure")
          img(src="https://mondrian.mashable.com/wp-content%252Fuploads%252F2013%252F12%252F131217_Twitter_Sprachen_Mashable_n.jpg%252Ffull-fit-in__1200x2000.jpg" alt="Chart: Only 34% of All Tweets are in English")
          figcaption Chart: Only 34% of All Tweets are in English. #[a(href="https://mashable.com/2013/12/17/twitter-popular-languages/") Statista via Mashable]

        ul: li Exact matching

        blockquote(class="article-blockquote") Exact matching of phrases (equivalent to quoted phrases in most search engines) is not supported. &mdash;#[a(href="https://developer.twitter.com/en/docs/tweets/filter-realtime/guides/basic-stream-parameters") Standard stream parameters]

        p Twitter matches a tweet as long as the words in one of the key phrases exists in the tweet, regardless of order. This means that a key phrase &ldquo;good night&rdquo; might match with a tweet posted in the morning that says, &ldquo;last night was good&rdquo;, resulting in some confusing or self-contradicting points in the viz.

        h2 Resulting musings

        ul

          li By looking at geolocation, the project is inherently biased towards people who are using their phones to tweet&mdash;the GPS capability of the phone makes it much easier, and in fact, I don&rsquo;t know if you can geotag your tweet from your laptop?

          li I haven&rsquo;t looked too much into data/research for this, but Twitter seemed to me to have developed from a semi-private journal for one&rsquo;s everyday happenings into a constant deluge of a whole world&rsquo;s very-public-facing declarations. These simple &ldquo;good morning&rdquo;s and &ldquo;good night&rdquo;s are a different side of modern Twitter I don&rsquo;t experience much on my feed.

          li Unlike a lot of time-based visualisations with defined time periods that you can scrub through to see as much at once as you want to, working with real-time data means you can only see the data that&rsquo;s coming in right now, which can be not very much at all. Waiting for data to come to you is either frustratingly limiting or edifyingly calming.